# I.Teaching and Primary Duties

## Summary

This year, my teaching and primary duties have been Superior. The narrative of my year is summarized as incremental success despite ever-changing obstacles.

Obviously, not all of these obstacles come from EIU. But a number of them do, and I think it well to introduce them into the "record," so to speak.

Institutional Obstacles to Teaching and Primary duties

- multi-year integration of two related but dissimilar academic departments.
- Ever-evolving, severe budget constraints, rearrangements and fund allocation shenanigans.
- Committee Cognitive Overload: The combination of departments into a school with still somewhat distinct branches while keeping in step with contractual obligations and IGPs created a borg-like hive of committee work that was poorly communicated across the school. Keeping track of all the various tangentially-related academic jargon *in addition to* course preparation and facilitation was a monumental cognitive load placed on a limited, already overcommitted faculty/staff/chair.
- Push toward LMS integration: This actually began when we moved away from Blackboard to Desire2Learn (D2L). There have been repeated efforts to grow faculty implementation and use, but success levels vary across many variables. **That push was exponentially increased when the Pandemic hit in March 2020.**
- Ever-evolving Equipment Constraints: These are interrelated, but all evolve around rapid technological change, investment in maintenance, life-cycle, changing student access to various technological tools. For instance, what once required a tape or disc to capture onto a video camera can now be done via Ethernet cables, Wi-Fi, Bluetooth and other means. Quality has been slowly democratized, but at the cost of complexity. Add to that ever-evolving external IT restraints and I am amazed there's a class every time one happens.

All of which means that there is an enormous amount of personal pedagogical adaptation that is not immediately evident in standard measurement criteria. So here I include the requested data, but add that the reality is much richer.

Student evaluations showed consistent high scores across the five standard questions on the Purdue Evaluation in both Spring and Fall 2020. These scores show a consistent and intentional increase over the past years.

I continued to improve integration of Learning Management Software (LMS) and associated web applications into course structures, especially JOU 3002 and JOU 1000.

  ### COVID-19 Educational Changes
Syllabi and course materials continue to evolve. This year, students in JOU 3002 worked with content management systems and (separately) social media networks, and regularly posting to these platforms, as well as keeping up with D2L/Office 365 and Zoom. We have done assignments requiring annotations in addition to creating blog posts, photo slideshows, timelines, maps, audio and video. I have also transitioned away from teaching the technology of multimedia and toward the practical and theoretical underpinnings, which has allowed students to develop their solution-seeking skills more, in addition to showcasing more student work during class time.

  ### Assessments

This year I served on the division curriculum committee as we discussed revisions to classes, prerequisites, learning objectives and personnel utilization.

Although some courses have not been offered this calendar year, their presence in the curriculum has stirred interest among students as they expand their educational plans.

This has thrown additional challenges into our ability/need to assess certain core classes according to our standard scales. I am currently participating in several efforts to better understand so-called "alternative scoring" methodologies - many spurred on by the Pandemic.

