# II. Research/Creative Activity

## Summary

My research and creative activity over the past year has been Significant.

I continued to work with two fellow artists in a studio in downtown Charleston, Gallery 619, which I concluded in December 2020.

I continued progress toward a BFA in 2D Studio Art through the Art + Design Department at EIU. My courses have been obviously hampered by the Pandemic situation, but I was able to complete courses in Spring 2020 (Computer Art I and Painting VI) and Fall 2020 (Computer Art, Painting V).

These courses have provided me with a broad base of knowledge that I've used to expand my research in Journalism and Media Literacy. I am currently investigating ways to use this interdisciplinary knowledge through digital humanities platforms. I have had the opportunity to informally work with various academics across campus and, indeed, the world through research and creative class projects. These connections allowed me to find additional resources for Journalism pedagogy, including design, photography, color theory, semiotics, philosophical and political movements and historical context.

I concluded my term as an Illinois Humanities Road Scholar in 2020, although I officially only spoke once after the beginning of the Pandemic. The pandemic increased interest in humanities presentations. Other political events further spurred that interest, and my project was not renewed.

However, participation in the project did allow me to work more closely with Illinois Humanities and other organizations with educational and cultural connections. This has allowed me to open the eyes of students to additional avenues in which they might use their communication skills in an ethical manner.

----------

# II. Service

## Summary

My service during the 2020 Calendar Year has been Superior

In Fall 2020, I began the most important service effort I have done for the division, serving as the chair for the search committee for a tenure-track Unit A faculty member to teach Photojournalism.

The effort – a challenge in “normal” times – was hindered by a pandemic, technological limitations, bureaucratic confusion, and the significance of this hire in the future of the division.

I continued to serve out the partial term I was elected to as Executive Assistant for UPI-EIU. I meet monthly with the union executive council and members of the wider academic labor community. Travel was restricted throughout 2020, but meetings continued regularly as local, state, and national governments, organizations and communities continued to adjust to the changing reality of the Covid-19 pandemic.

Throughout 2020 I served where asked on School and Department committees, which waxed and waned in frequency according to the larger changes within the university.

On a university level, I am involved in several committees/organizations that are symbiotic between my union duties and my faculty service duties. This includes Title IX Dispute Training, Legislative Action Committees, higher education planning/coordinating sessions - both local and national.

I'm not going to list all of that here. Suffice to say that the service on the Search Committee and the EIU-UPI executive board has meant I have had an abundance of service over the calendar year.

Finally, throughout the year I have served as an unofficial resource for other faculty and staff on technical issues with classroom and office computers and online resources. This includes troubleshooting unexpected technology issues, advising on using Office 365 and other campus software, and sharing information about broader technological changes in the industry.
